comments.text:
I think people are more upset about the depressing feeling the end of the episode left. Bartleby goes out of his way to make a compassionate gesture to the entire town by giving everyone a free tree. His good will is immediately rejected by the townspeople who just prior were clamoring to find ways to purchase those same trees on layaway. The episode ends here with Bartleby walking away dejected, receiving no vindication for his kindness. It's a shocking twist that's unexpected for a season as joyous as Christmas. Though this is also why I think the criticism is unfounded. Tamers is an artist who is known for going against the formulaic trends of modern media in order to create something much greater than the common trite on television. This reversal of the merry Christmas atmosphere is avant-garde. A complete deconstruction of the ostracizing market-obsessed nature of the holiday. This interpretation is a much more realistic one than any past Christmas related media has ever portrayed. Merriment and togetherness are not something a scheduled yearly holiday can simply will into existence. Sometimes the emotional gaps between people are too large to bridge. Sometimes you may work very hard for someone and they won't show any appreciation for it. Christmas may be about smiles, but sometimes it brings tears. This cartoon was brave enough to touch upon that.

Knuckles was right to be mad at his grandpa in this episode. It's not Bartleby's fault that the echidna family can't afford a tree, it's their own. They weren't just financially bankrupt but morally bankrupt as well. They didn't deserve a Christmas, and if you still think Bartleby was wrong than you don't either.
